00:17:44,760 --> 00:17:53,640
but you could tell if... One founder, I'll give 
a story, one founder, once we asked a question  

179
00:17:53,640 --> 00:17:59,800
and one person started to respond and the other 
founder put his arm in front of him and said,  

180
00:17:59,800 --> 00:18:07,520
"I'll answer that question." And it was just so 
weird that he wouldn't let his co-founder speak.  

181
00:18:07,520 --> 00:18:13,520
We'd have situations where we'd call people 
like hackers in a cage, where it's kind of  

182
00:18:13,520 --> 00:18:22,560
obvious there'd be a business founder, business 
person, who had clearly convinced a programmer to  

183
00:18:22,560 --> 00:18:29,680
join the team. They were given, the programmer was 
given, very little equity and just we called them  

184
00:18:29,680 --> 00:18:36,400
programmers in a cage, like hackers in a cage. 
And sometimes that works out, I'm not saying it  

185
00:18:36,400 --> 00:18:44,760
doesn't. But I'd always try to observe, okay, does 
this hacker in a cage have any say in the company,  

186
00:18:44,760 --> 00:18:50,480
the direction of the product? That sort of thing. 
Because the programmer needs to have opinions.
 

187
00:18:50,480 --> 00:18:56,280
It's so funny. I love this metaphor. And I 
totally get what you mean. I want to unpack  

188
00:18:56,280 --> 00:19:01,000
a couple of these, because this is exactly where 
I was hoping we'd go. So this idea of looking for  

189
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:06,600
defensiveness and being open to change and being 
flexible, why do you think that was so important  

190
00:19:06,600 --> 00:19:10,520
to successful founders? Why did you look for 
that? Why was that a predictor of success?
 

191
00:19:10,520 --> 00:19:16,720
Several things. First of all, being defensive 
is really bad, if you're a startup founder,  

192
00:19:16,720 --> 00:19:23,800
because you're always going to get people who 
question you. And it's your job to educate them,  

193
00:19:23,800 --> 00:19:28,720
if it's a new area, you're doing 
something presumably pretty new,  

194
00:19:28,720 --> 00:19:34,200
you're always going to have people who question 
it or say, "That product's already out there,  

195
00:19:34,200 --> 00:19:40,280
why is yours better?" You have to educate them. 
You don't want to be defensive about it. Also,  

196
00:19:40,280 --> 00:19:47,920
a lot of times, the first idea isn't bang right 
on, the right idea, and you have to be open-minded  

197
00:19:47,920 --> 00:19:54,120
and maybe adjust it in a certain direction. 
The famous PayPal story, how it started off  

198
00:19:54,120 --> 00:20:03,160
being the PalmPilot, or money transfer. And money 
transfer between the PalmPilots or whatever. And  

199
00:20:03,160 --> 00:20:10,000
then all the customers were using a janky version 
on the web, and they were begging for this to be  

200
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:15,240
on the web. And finally, the founder said, "Oh, 
I see what most people want this for." You have  

201
00:20:15,240 --> 00:20:22,720
to be open-minded to see what direction really is 
what your users want. And so if you find someone  

202
00:20:22,720 --> 00:20:30,480
is defensive, usually they're not open-minded.
The other thing is that the best founders will  

203
00:20:30,480 --> 00:20:38,320
want to learn from other people and listen to 
other people. You talk to the Collison brothers  

204
00:20:38,320 --> 00:20:44,680
and say something, they ask you a question, 
they're listening to your answer. So many founders  

205
00:20:44,680 --> 00:20:51,320
think, oh, I can't learn from anyone. But the best 
founders are always listening and having spirited  

206
00:20:51,320 --> 00:20:57,320
debates about things. I mean, that's part of the 
process. And so I think when someone's defensive,  

207
00:20:57,320 --> 00:21:05,120
it's just a bad sign. So I would look for that.
I loved when I'd find someone sort of showcase  

208
00:21:05,120 --> 00:21:10,480
that they'd make something happen 
no matter what; they're scrappy,  

209
00:21:10,480 --> 00:21:17,600
they're hustlers. I remember... Can I tell 
the story about the Airbnb interview?
 

210
00:21:17,600 --> 00:21:19,880
Please.
Okay, because that was definitely  

211
00:21:19,880 --> 00:21:26,800
one I'll never forget. That was one that was clear 
the founders were really good. The market had just  

212
00:21:26,800 --> 00:21:33,440
crashed basically with all the banks going out 
of business and everything. And so we were only  

213
00:21:33,440 --> 00:21:40,360
funding startups that we felt had really scrappy 
founders and could be cockroaches, meaning could  

214
00:21:40,360 --> 00:21:45,280
live off of very little amounts of money, or 
could charge customers and make money. And we  

215
00:21:45,280 --> 00:21:50,800
didn't fund that many people in that winter '09 
batch. So we're being very strict with ourselves,  

216
00:21:50,800 --> 00:21:59,560
very disciplined about things. And the Airbnb guys 
came in, and I just remember they had a contagious  

217
00:21:59,560 --> 00:22:07,080
amount of energy. They just had an energy about 
them the way that they talked about their product,  

218
00:22:07,080 --> 00:22:15,040
which was crazy at the time, staying in someone's 
bed or airbed. In fact, it's a famous part of the  

219
00:22:15,040 --> 00:22:21,200
story, we hated their idea and Paul tried to get 
Brian and Joe and Nate to change it. So we didn't  

220
00:22:21,200 --> 00:22:27,000
even like the idea. But I remember specifically 
they brought, at the end, Joe brought out these,  

221
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:33,224
the cereal boxes, the Obama O's and Cap'n 
Crunch's or Cap'n McCain's or whatever.
 

222
00:22:33,224 --> 00:22:38,800
Cap'n McCain's, yeah.
Yeah, Cap'n McCain's. They were saying that  

223
00:22:38,800 --> 00:22:48,080
they went to some Costco or something and bought 
off-brand Cheerios and off-brand Cap'n Crunch's,  

224
00:22:48,080 --> 00:22:54,440
took them out of the box, put them in this new 
box, glue-gunned it shut. And I just thought,  

225
00:22:54,440 --> 00:23:00,040
oh my God, these guys are really going to 
great lengths for this. And for some reason,  

226
00:23:00,040 --> 00:23:04,760
it was silly, but it really appealed to me. 
They're going to work hard to do whatever  

227
00:23:04,760 --> 00:23:10,960
they can to make this company succeed. And even 
though we were skeptical about the idea, I think  

228
00:23:10,960 --> 00:23:16,880
we definitely made the right bet on the founders, 
and it was just very clear in that interview.
 

229
00:23:16,880 --> 00:23:19,720
I'm so happy you shared that story, I 
was definitely going to ask about it.  

230
00:23:19,720 --> 00:23:24,360
It's so funny because I've heard that story 
at least a hundred times working at Airbnb,  

231
00:23:25,240 --> 00:23:31,200
they tell the beginning of Airbnb every chance 
they get at every all-hands. It's like a recurring  

232
00:23:31,200 --> 00:23:36,120
theme. And it's great to hear that basically it 
went exactly the way they describe. Oftentimes,  

233
00:23:36,120 --> 00:23:40,760
there's a myth around what happened, but 
that's exactly how they describe it.
 

234
00:23:40,760 --> 00:23:47,160
No, it was definitely a whole crazy story and how 
Paul called them to accept them, and they were on  

235
00:23:47,160 --> 00:23:53,120
the 280 or something or the 101 and the reception 
went down. And so he didn't hear if they were  

236
00:23:53,120 --> 00:23:58,720
accepted or not. Did he tell that part?
No, I haven't heard that part.
 

237
00:23:58,720 --> 00:24:04,760
Oh yeah, that's part of the story. And they 
had to keep driving to get to talk to Paul  

238
00:24:04,760 --> 00:24:10,200
again and find out that they were accepted. 
Oh, yeah. It was just a crazy interview.
 

239
00:24:10,200 --> 00:24:14,600
The element of the story I'm also curious about 
is, the way Joe tells it, is he had the box in his  

240
00:24:14,600 --> 00:24:19,680
backpack. And as they were walking out, Paul or 
you is like, "Hey, what's that? What's that cereal  

241
00:24:19,680 --> 00:24:24,280
box doing there?" Is that how it went, or is it 
more like, "Hey, we have this cereal thing."?
 

242
00:24:24,280 --> 00:24:31,040
I don't think Paul and I looked in his backpack 
and asked. I think there was definitely some  

243
00:24:31,040 --> 00:24:38,120
pressure on Joe not to show us the cereal 
boxes. I think Nate was really down on that,  

244
00:24:38,120 --> 00:24:42,600
especially. And I think they were walking 
out the door and they're like, "Hey,  

245
00:24:42,600 --> 00:24:49,000
we just brought you a little something." I think 
Joe did pull it out, and we had an extra minute or  

246
00:24:49,000 --> 00:24:53,760
so around the cereal boxes. That's how I heard 
about the glue gun story and everything. But  

247
00:24:53,760 --> 00:25:00,040
I think Joe had been reluctant, but he did it 
at the end and I think it was a good call.
 

248
00:25:00,040 --> 00:25:05,240
That's so funny. And after that meeting, what 
was that conversation like between you and Paul?  

249
00:25:05,240 --> 00:25:08,560
Was it just like everyone's like, "We definitely 
got to do this."? Or was it like you being like,  

250
00:25:08,560 --> 00:25:12,720
"Hey, these guys are really interesting."?
No, I think we all liked them. We all liked  

251
00:25:12,720 --> 00:25:17,680
them. But I remember saying, "We have got to..." 
I just remember being like, "We've got to fund  

252
00:25:17,680 --> 00:25:23,040
these guys. I don't know about the idea. Maybe 
they'll change their idea, who knows? But they  

253
00:25:23,040 --> 00:25:30,040
seem really great." Again, the energy level 
and the passion with which they spoke about  

254
00:25:30,040 --> 00:25:36,320
their experience hosting, because they'd been 
around struggling, but had been a company with  

255
00:25:36,320 --> 00:25:42,000
an idea for a little while before they applied 
to YC. We were there basically their Hail Mary,  

256
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:51,320
their last resort for them. And so they could tell 
us about their story about how they hosted the  

257
00:25:51,320 --> 00:25:57,400
people at a conference, and there was definitely 
some magic to it, which was convincing.
 

258
00:25:57,400 --> 00:25:59,920
Is there anything else along the 
Airbnb story that would be interesting  

259
00:25:59,920 --> 00:26:03,520
to share while we're on that topic?
I mean, the only interesting thing as it  

260
00:26:03,520 --> 00:26:08,560
relates to being the social radar is that there 
were just some interviews that I remember because  

261
00:26:08,560 --> 00:26:16,400
I just thought, this is great. These founders 
are so good. I'm totally convinced. What they're  

262
00:26:16,400 --> 00:26:22,280
working on might not work, but I feel like it's 
so worth the bet based on these founders. And  

263
00:26:22,280 --> 00:26:28,320
that happened. There were definitely a couple 
other of our most successful companies that I  

264
00:26:28,320 --> 00:26:32,440
clearly felt that way about. You just feel 
like they know what they're talking about,  

265
00:26:32,440 --> 00:26:39,840
they thought about the problem. They're not 
solving this problem because it's sort of the  

266
00:26:39,840 --> 00:26:48,520
problem du jour or fun and exciting. Some are very 
unsexy problems like when Parker Conrad applied  

267
00:26:48,520 --> 00:26:57,320
with Zenefits, unsexy HR stuff, benefits stuff. 
But he knew how broken it was and was trying to  

268
00:26:57,320 --> 00:27:05,240
fix it. And I love stories like that. There was 
one story in terms of... The one time I did sort  

269
00:27:05,240 --> 00:27:13,000
of persuade the rest of the group to fund someone 
was, do you know the company GOAT, the sneaker?
 

270
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:17,880
Absolutely.
Okay. When Eddie and Daishin applied,  

271
00:27:17,880 --> 00:27:26,040
they were not doing the sneaker company, they were 
doing this group sort of book-a-group-dinner at  

272
00:27:26,040 --> 00:27:30,960
a restaurant with people you don't know as a 
way to meet new people. And for some reason,  

273
00:27:30,960 --> 00:27:35,400
I loved the idea because I thought maybe 
it could be a secret dating, like a Trojan  

274
00:27:35,400 --> 00:27:41,240
Horse for a dating sort of site. But I really 
loved the two founders. And one of the reasons,  

275
00:27:41,240 --> 00:27:50,880
again, they had this passion about their idea, but 
they had had this cream puff company before that  

276
00:27:50,880 --> 00:27:55,880
they had run, and they just told these stories 
about how hard it was and all this stuff. And I,  

277
00:27:55,880 --> 00:28:00,840
for some reason, just thought, these are hustlers. 
These guys are scrappy. They're going to make  

278
00:28:00,840 --> 00:28:08,640
this succeed. And they didn't make that company 
succeed, but they pivoted and made GOAT succeed  

279
00:28:08,640 --> 00:28:14,720
and it's doing really, really well. And I remember 
that one I definitely had to convince... I mean,  

280
00:28:14,720 --> 00:28:19,960
not that Paul, Robert and Trevor didn't like 
them, but I think they really didn't think  

281
00:28:19,960 --> 00:28:24,040
the idea was that great or just sort of were 
meh. I was like, "We have to fund them."
 

282
00:28:24,040 --> 00:28:27,680
I love sharing these stories. If you have more 
to share, please keep throwing them out there.
 

283
00:28:27,680 --> 00:28:32,000
So a few things I've noted so far, of things 
that you look for, and I think it's important to  

284
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:38,320
note this is very early stage evaluation where 
the founder and the team is, it's incredibly  

285
00:28:38,320 --> 00:28:44,000
important, because the idea often shifts.
Oh, yeah. This is as early as it gets, Lenny.
 

286
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:48,760
Yeah. Oftentimes, just an idea, I imagine.
Yes.
 

287
00:28:48,760 --> 00:28:55,560
So a few things, so far, things that you found 
to be really valuable to look for. One is this  

288
00:28:55,560 --> 00:29:00,920
idea of just making shit happen, showing signs 
of being hustlers, just getting shit done,  

289
00:29:00,920 --> 00:29:06,480
Obama O's, things like that. And then I think 
along the same lines, just passion for this  

290
00:29:06,480 --> 00:29:11,280
idea and just like almost charisma. Is that how 
you think about it? Or is it just like...
 

291
00:29:11,280 --> 00:29:21,240
I hate using the word charisma because there are a 
lot of charismatic people who are full of baloney,  

292
00:29:21,240 --> 00:29:26,360
and are just doing a startup because it's a cool 
thing to do now. And I wouldn't want anyone to  

293
00:29:26,360 --> 00:29:33,520
get fooled by charisma. There has to be some 
substance behind that charisma. Of course,  

294
00:29:33,520 --> 00:29:39,200
we all love talking to more charismatic people 
than less, and I've certainly talked to my  

295
00:29:39,200 --> 00:29:44,280
fair share of totally uncharismatic people, 
but sometimes they're really good founders  

296
00:29:44,280 --> 00:29:52,200
too. If they know what they're doing and care 
about the user and are fixing a problem that  

297
00:29:52,200 --> 00:29:58,040
they have a deep connection to. So I don't 
want to say someone who's charismatic, but  

298
00:29:58,560 --> 00:30:04,720
it definitely helps because, as you know, as a 
founder, you have to do a lot of sales and you  

299
00:30:04,720 --> 00:30:10,920
have to recruit people and you have to convince 
investors to fund you and you have to convince  

300
00:30:10,920 --> 00:30:18,880
users to use your product and all of this stuff. 
So it does help being charismatic, definitely.
 

301
00:30:18,880 --> 00:30:23,120
Okay. So there's being super hustler, 
making shit happen. Domain expertise,  

302
00:30:23,120 --> 00:30:26,720
something you've mentioned a few times. Just 
like having deep domain expertise in an area,  

303
00:30:26,720 --> 00:30:31,200
and I think that's probably where they probably 
don't pivot oftentimes, where they've actually  

304
00:30:31,200 --> 00:30:35,680
have experience in that specific problem.
They might pivot a little bit, they might pivot  

305
00:30:35,680 --> 00:30:40,360
a little in terms of the actual solution. 
They might be trying to solve a problem  

306
00:30:40,360 --> 00:30:45,240
and the first attempt doesn't really work. 
I haven't mentioned earnestness though.
 

307
00:30:45,240 --> 00:30:48,960
Oh, do tell.
Earnestness is one of  

308
00:30:48,960 --> 00:30:58,440
the most important because earnest, sort of to 
me, is bucketed with authenticity. And to be a  

309
00:30:58,440 --> 00:31:04,480
successful startup founder, you have to care so 
much about the problem you're trying to solve,  

310
00:31:04,480 --> 00:31:14,320
the users you're serving and being earnest about 
it is so key to success. There are so many wannabe  

311
00:31:14,320 --> 00:31:22,360
founders, so many people doing it because it's 
cool or they think this idea is cool, but they  

312
00:31:22,360 --> 00:31:29,840
don't really, deep down, have what it takes. And 
I think we always try to fund earnest people.
 

313
00:31:29,840 --> 00:31:33,600
What does earnest look like in practice? 
And how does that come across?
 

314
00:31:33,600 --> 00:31:41,160
I think it means being sort of humble about... And 
if you get asked a question in the interview and  

315
00:31:41,160 --> 00:31:48,040
you don't know the answer, they say, "I don't know 
the answer to that. I'd have to think about it."  

316
00:31:48,040 --> 00:31:53,360
Or, "I don't know the answer. I've given it some 
thought and here's what I have come up with." And  

317
00:31:53,360 --> 00:31:59,640
they're just honest about things, and they're not 
trying to do the whole smoke and mirrors thing,  

318
00:31:59,640 --> 00:32:03,560
which we've definitely gotten people 
like that, that avoid the question  

319
00:32:03,560 --> 00:32:12,160
or are doing it for the wrong reasons.
I remember there was one group that were  

320
00:32:12,760 --> 00:32:21,920
45-year-old men and they were building an 
app for teenagers in fashion. And I remember  

321
00:32:21,920 --> 00:32:27,560
just thinking, we were asking them, "Why have you 
chosen teenagers in fashion?" And it was so clear  

322
00:32:27,560 --> 00:32:33,600
that they thought they could make easy money, 
and it wasn't because they cared about fashion.  

323
00:32:33,600 --> 00:32:39,000
It wasn't because, "Oh, I have a daughter who's 
really into fashion and I've seen this need." It  

324
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:47,080
was just like, they made up the idea. And that 
is not earnest, that is not authentic to me.
 

325
00:32:47,080 --> 00:32:52,080
You talked about it, so there's this earnestness 
you look for, also not being defensive. There's  

326
00:32:52,080 --> 00:32:56,680
this also spectrum of confidence and people 
believing in what they're doing. Do you have  

327
00:32:56,680 --> 00:33:00,000
any thoughts on just how to find that? 
What does that look like when they're too  

328
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:03,280
defensive versus they're just confident and 
then they know what they're talking about?
 

329
00:33:03,280 --> 00:33:09,160
Confidence is good. You definitely want 
confidence. It's hard to... I think you  

330
00:33:09,160 --> 00:33:17,760
can see it when you experience it. Like someone 
who's confident in answering your questions but  

331
00:33:17,760 --> 00:33:22,440
isn't defensive, there's definitely a difference. 
And I don't know, this is why I'm saying it's sort  

332
00:33:22,440 --> 00:33:27,880
of hard to articulate these things, but confidence 
means you can say, "I've thought about that and I  

333
00:33:27,880 --> 00:33:32,880
don't know the answer." That's confidence. 
And they'll say, "But here's what I do to  

334
00:33:32,880 --> 00:33:40,800
try to figure it out. Here are my plans to 
address that." Confidence, I should have put  

335
00:33:40,800 --> 00:33:46,360
that upfront because that's very important, 
especially when it comes to fundraising,  

336
00:33:47,400 --> 00:33:52,720
you cannot go into an investor meeting lacking 
confidence. You can come into YC's interview  

337
00:33:52,720 --> 00:33:58,680
lacking confidence, but we will then help you in 
the next three months to gain more confidence.
 

338
00:33:58,680 --> 00:34:04,240
And by the way, one of the things we do to 
help people gain more confidence is to make  

339
00:34:04,240 --> 00:34:10,040
them believe that their startup is a great 
investment, to help them create a startup  

340
00:34:10,040 --> 00:34:17,000
that truly is possibly going to make money or at 
least worth being a good bet. That's the thing,  

341
00:34:17,000 --> 00:34:25,320
early stage, the best you can offer is like, "I 
might not succeed, but I'm definitely a good bet."  

342
00:34:25,320 --> 00:34:31,400
And we help them with their product, we help 
them with their ideas, and we help them that,  

343
00:34:31,400 --> 00:34:37,200
by demo day, they can get up on stage and 
legitimately say, "We're a good bet and  

344
00:34:37,200 --> 00:34:43,440
here's why. Let me tell you about our idea." 
And so we definitely help with confidence.
 

345
00:34:43,440 --> 00:34:47,600
Awesome. A couple other things you mentioned 
earlier, just to unpack a little bit. So being  

346
00:34:47,600 --> 00:34:53,040
committed, something you look for, and co-founders 
getting along. In terms of committed, I imagine,  

347
00:34:53,040 --> 00:34:57,840
these are very practical things. How are 
they actually going to stick to this? Are  

348
00:34:57,840 --> 00:35:00,520
they actually excited to work on this? 
Maybe talk about that a little bit.
 

349
00:35:00,520 --> 00:35:06,160
We all know how hard startups are, but I think 
you don't really know how hard it is until you  

350
00:35:06,160 --> 00:35:12,080
actually do it. A lot of people would start a 
startup still having a job at Google or wherever,  

351
00:35:12,080 --> 00:35:16,800
and they do it on the side. I do recommend, 
if people are just getting started and don't  

352
00:35:16,800 --> 00:35:22,040
want to raise money yet, starting it on the 
side is a great way to get going, but at some  

353
00:35:22,040 --> 00:35:27,840
point you have to commit, you have to burn the 
boat, because we found that founders who were  

354
00:35:27,840 --> 00:35:34,720
still getting a paycheck and health insurance, 
once the going got tough, they did not quit their  

355
00:35:34,720 --> 00:35:44,640
job. And you sort of need that desperation 
